ent with Contemporary People and Current Issues -- tIntroduction -- t9. Archaeology, Historical Ecology, and the Revitalization of Indigenous Land Stewardship -- t10. Telling Survivance: Connecting the Past with Present in Archaeologies of Colonialism -- t11. An Archaeology of Multiethnicity in Hawaiian Ranching Communities -- t12. Rethinking “Long-Term”: Time Immemorial and Archaeology in an Era of Self-Dealing and Sacrilegious Destruction -- tPart IV. Conducting Archaeology with Honor, Humor, and Humility -- tIntroduction -- t13. Transformative Relationships and Enduring Partnerships in Archaeological Practice -- t14. Curios and Collections: The Lightfoot Lab Legacy through Little Things Left Behind -- t15. A Testament to Kent Lightfoot’s Academic Legacy -- t16. Lightfoot Living: Practicing Humility, Care, and Collaboration in Archaeology -- tAfterword -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a dynamic near half-century career of insight, engagement, and instruction, Kent G. Lightfoot transformed North American archaeology through his innovative ideas, robust collaborations, thoughtful field projects, and mentoring of numerous students. Authors emphasize the multifarious ways Lightfoot impacted—and continues to impact—approaches to archaeological inquiry, anthropological engagement, Indigenous issues, and professionalism. Four primary themes include: negotiations of intercultural entanglements in pluralistic settings; transformations of temporal and spatial archaeological dimensions, as well as theoretical and methodological innovations; engagement with contemporary people and issues; and leading by example with honor, humor, and humility. These reflect the remarkable depth, breadth, and growth in Lightfoot’s career, despite his unwavering stylistic devotion to Hawaiian shirts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online